We will use penguins_data (generated for you below) to build various models of penguin body_mass_g. Throughout, we’ll utilize weakly informative priors and a basic understanding that the average penguin weighs somewhere between 3,500 and 4,500 grams. One predictor of interest is penguin species: Adelie or Gentoo.

penguin_data <- penguins_bayes %>% 
  filter(species %in% c("Adelie", "Gentoo")) %>%
  select(flipper_length_mm, body_mass_g, species) %>% 
  na.omit()

1. Modeling Main Effects (3pt)

Let’s begin our analysis of penguin body_mass_g by exploring its relationship with flipper_length_mm and species.

Q: Plot and summarize the observed relationships among these three variables. (0.5pt)

Hint: use ggplot() and set color = species to color the two types of penguins differently.

ggplot(penguin_data, aes(y = body_mass_g, x = flipper_length_mm, color = species)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)

SUMMARY: Body mass increases as flipper length increases (no matter the species); body mass tends to be higher among Gentoo penguins compared to Adelie penguins (lower mean, minimum, and maximum mass among Adelie penguins)

Q: Use stan_glm() to simulate a posterior Normal regression model of body_mass_g by flipper_length_mm and species, without an interaction term. (0.5pt)

penguin_main <- stan_glm(
  body_mass_g ~ flipper_length_mm + species, 
  data = penguin_data, family = gaussian, 
  prior_intercept = normal(4000, 250), 
  prior = normal(0, 2.5, autoscale = TRUE), 
  prior_aux = exponential(1, autoscale = TRUE),
  chains = 4, iter = 5000*2, seed = 84735)

INTERPRETATION: Density plots of individual chains produce almost identical posterior approximations, indicating the MCMC simulation is stable and runs long enough Trace plots overlap well and do not go up or down over time, and autocorrelation drops quickly for all parameters; this indicates that the MCMC simulation is fast-mixing/works well Effective sample size ratios are greater than 0.1 and R-hat is close to 1 (less than 1.05) for all parameters, also indicating that the MCMC simulation is working well

Q: Produce a tidy() summary of this model. Interpret the non-intercept coefficients’ posterior median values in context. (0.5pt)

tidy(penguin_main, effects = c("fixed", "aux"),
     conf.int = TRUE, conf.level = 0.80) %>% 
  select(-std.error)

INTERPRETATION: The penguins body masses increase by about 42.58779 for every millimeter increase in flipper length. The typical Gentoo penguin’s body mass is about 216.13722 grams higher than the typical Adelie penguin’s body mass.

Q: Simulate, plot, and describe the posterior predictive model for the body mass of an Adelie penguin that has a flipper length of 197. (1pt)

set.seed(84735)

                       species = c("Adelie")))

2. Modeling Interaction (3pt)

Building from the previous exercise, our next goal is to model body_mass_g by flipper_length_mm and species with an interaction term between these two predictors.

Q: Use stan_glm() to simulate the posterior for this model, with four chains at 10,000 iterations each. (1pt)

penguin_interact <- stan_glm(
  body_mass_g ~ flipper_length_mm + species + flipper_length_mm:species, 
  data = penguin_data, family = gaussian, 
  prior_intercept = normal(4000, 250), 
  prior = normal(0, 2.5, autoscale = TRUE), 
  prior_aux = exponential(1, autoscale = TRUE),
  chains = 4, iter = 5000*2, seed = 84735)

Q: Simulate and plot 50 posterior model lines. Briefly describe what you learn from this plot. (1pt)

penguin_data %>%
  add_fitted_draws(penguin_interact, n = 50) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = flipper_length_mm, y = body_mass_g, color = species)) +
    geom_line(aes(y = .value, group = paste(species, .draw)), alpha = 0.1)
Warning: `fitted_draws` and `add_fitted_draws` are deprecated as their names were confusing.
Use [add_]epred_draws() to get the expectation of the posterior predictive.
Use [add_]linpred_draws() to get the distribution of the linear predictor.
For example, you used [add_]fitted_draws(..., scale = "response"), which
means you most likely want [add_]epred_draws(...).

DESCRIPTION: Generally, the Gentoo posterior models are slightly more positive (in slope) than the Adelie posterior models. This implies that the association between flipper length and species is slightly more positive for Gentoo penguins than for Adelie ones.

Q: Produce a tidy() summary for this model. Based on the summary, do you have evidence that the interaction terms are necessary for this model? Explain your reasoning. (1pt)

tidy(penguin_interact, effects = c("fixed", "aux"))

INTERPRETATION: According to the summary, the association between body mass and flipper length is different between species. Gentoo penguins generally gain about 1.5 times more body mass per mm in flipper length compared to Adelaide penguins: 34.61639 + 17.35665 (or 51.97304) grams per millimeter compared to 34.61630 grams per millimeter. Since the association is different between species, interaction terms are necessary for this model.

3. Model Comparison (4pt)

Q: Produce and compare the pp_check() plots for both models above (penguin_main and penguin_interact). (1pt)

pp_check(penguin_main)

pp_check(penguin_interact)

COMPARISON: Both models seem to have trouble with the second/right-hand mode; they place it around 5000, when it should be less (around 4750) according to the plot. The penguin_interact model places more mass at the first/left mode and less mass at the second mode compared to the penguin-main model, but they both place more mass at the first mode than the second.

Q: Use 10-fold cross-validation to assess and compare the posterior predictive quality of the two models using prediction_summary_cv(). (1pt)

Note: this step might take some time! In addition, you will want to set.seed() at some seed value before running prediction_summary_cv() in order to reproduce your results.

COMPARISON: penguin_main has a smaller mae and mae_scaled than penguin_interact, and it has a greater within_95 coverage statistic. While penguin_interact has a greater within_50 statistic, penguin_main slightly outperforms it by any other measure that prediction_summary_cv() provides.

Q: In summary, which one of the two models is ``better?’’ Explain. (1pt)

The penguin_interact (the model with the interaction term) is the better model. While the posterior predictive check and 10-fold cross-validation suggest there is only a slight difference in accuracy, the fact that penguin_interact has a greater ELPD indicates that it is the more accurate model. Furthermore, since there is a difference in association between body mass and flipper length across species according to the posterior model lines and tidy() summary (although this difference is not extreme), it should be helpful to use the model with interaction terms.
